SENATE BILL 943
P2 6lr3434
CF 6lr3444
By: Senator Charles
Introduced and read first time: February 6, 2026
Assigned to: Budget and Taxation
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 State Procurement – Competitive Sealed Bids and Proposals – In–State
3 Evaluation Preference
4 (Buy Maryland, Buy Local Act)
5 FOR the purpose of requiring competitive sealed bids and proposals to be awarded based
6 on certain standardized evaluation criteria; requiring the criteria to be included in
7 an invitation for bids or a request for proposals; requiring a responsive bid or
8 proposal to include a certain State and local economic impact statement; and
9 generally relating to State procurement.
10 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
11 Article – State Finance and Procurement
12 Section 13–103 and 13–104
13 Annotated Code of Maryland
14 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
15 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
16 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
17 Article – State Finance and Procurement
18 13–103.
19 (a) (1) Whenever procurement is based on competitive sealed bids, a
20 procurement officer shall seek bids by issuing an invitation for bids.
21 (2) Subject to subsection (b) of this section, an invitation for bids shall
22 include:
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *sb0943*

2 SENATE BILL 943
1 (i) the specifications of the procurement contract, including the
2 expected degree of minority business enterprise participation, as provided in § 14–303(b) of
3 this article;
4 (ii) a summary of the factors used to determine the expected degree
5 of minority business enterprise participation for the procurement contract, including
6 subcontracting opportunities identified for the project, any applicable North American
7 Industry Classification System codes linked to the subcontracting opportunities, and the
8 number of certified minority business enterprises in those industries;
9 (iii) [whether the procurement contract will be awarded based on the
10 lowest bid price, the lowest evaluated bid price or, if the procurement is subject to §
11 11–202(3) of this article,] THE STANDARDIZED EVALUATION CRITERIA UNDER
12 SUBSECTION (G) OF THIS SECTION FOR DETERMINING the bid most favorable to the
13 State; AND
14 (iv) [if the procurement contract will be based on evaluated bid price,
15 the objective measurable criteria by which the lowest evaluated bid price will be
16 determined; and
17 (v)] if the head of the unit or the head of the unit’s designee has so
18 designated, the small business preference.
19 (b) (1) Whenever a procurement officer determines that an initial preparation
20 of specifications for price bids is impracticable, the invitation for bids may:
21 (i) include a request for unpriced technical offers or samples; and
22 (ii) direct bidders to submit price bids:
23 1. with the unpriced technical offers or samples; or
24 2. after the unit evaluates the technical offers or samples and
25 finds that they are acceptable under the criteria set forth in the invitation for bids.
26 (2) A unit shall consider the prices submitted by bidders whose technical
27 offers or samples have been found acceptable.
28 (3) Price bids may not be opened until after the unit has completed
29 evaluation of the technical offers or samples.
30 (4) (i) A price bid may not be opened at any time if the bid is submitted
31 by a bidder whose technical offer or sample has been evaluated as unacceptable to the unit.
32 (ii) A procurement officer shall return an unopened price bid
33 submitted by a bidder whose technical offer or sample has been evaluated as unacceptable.

SENATE BILL 943 3
1 (c) (1) A unit shall give public notice of an invitation for bids before bid
2 opening in accordance with this subsection.
3 (2) A unit shall give reasonable notice that shall be at least 10 days before
4 bid opening.
5 (3) The unit shall publish notice in eMaryland Marketplace at least 20 days
6 before bid opening if:
7 (i) the procurement officer reasonably expects bid prices to exceed
8 the small procurement amount specified in § 13–109 of this subtitle or a lower amount set
9 by the Board by regulation in accordance with Title 10, Subtitle 1 of the State Government
10 Article; and
11 (ii) at least part of the procurement contract is to be performed in
12 this State or the District of Columbia.
13 (4) In addition to any notice required under this subsection, a unit may
14 publish notice of an invitation for bids:
15 (i) on a bid board or eMaryland Marketplace; or
16 (ii) in a newspaper, periodical, or trade journal.
17 (d) (1) A procurement officer shall:
18 (i) open bids in public at the time and place designated in the
19 invitation for bids; and
20 (ii) announce, record, and post:
21 1. the name of each bidder; and
22 2. the amount of each bid.
23 (2) Except as provided in paragraph (3) of this subsection, a bid is
24 irrevocable, after bid opening, for the period specified in the invitation for bids.
25 (3) A procurement officer may allow a bidder to correct or withdraw a bid
26 if correction or withdrawal is:
27 (i) allowed under regulations adopted under this Division II; and
28 (ii) approved in writing by the Office of the Attorney General.

4 SENATE BILL 943
1 (e) (1) After obtaining any approval required by law, the procurement officer
2 shall award the procurement contract to the responsible bidder who submits the responsive
3 bid that[:
4 (i) is the lowest bid price;
5 (ii) if the invitation for bids so provides, is the lowest evaluated bid
6 price; or
7 (iii) for procurement subject to § 11–202(3) of this article,] is the bid
8 most favorable to the State UNDER THE STANDARDIZED EVALUATION CRITERIA
9 UNDER SUBSECTION (G) OF THIS SECTION.
10 (2) If, after competitive sealed bids have been opened, a procurement
11 officer determines that only 1 responsible bidder has submitted a responsive bid, the unit
12 may negotiate the procurement contract with that 1 bidder under the procedure for sole
13 source procurement.
14 (3) (i) After competitive sealed bids have been opened, a procurement
15 officer may award a procurement contract on the basis of revised bids if:
16 1. all bids are rejected under § 13–206(b) of this title;
17 2. all bid prices exceed the funds available for the
18 procurement; or
19 3. with the approval of the head of the unit or a designee, the
20 procurement officer determines that all bids are unreasonable as to at least 1 requirement
21 and the delay that would result from issuing a new invitation for bids with revised
22 specifications or quantities would be fiscally disadvantageous or otherwise not in the best
23 interests of the State.
24 (ii) If there is more than 1 bidder, discussions about revised
25 specifications or quantities shall be conducted with all responsible bidders who submitted
26 responsive bids. The bidders shall be treated fairly and equally with respect to any
27 discussions.
28 (iii) As promptly as possible, the procurement officer shall:
29 1. issue an invitation for revised bids, which shall state
30 whether the award will be made without competitive negotiations; and
31 2. require a prompt response to that invitation.
32 (iv) An invitation for revised bids is not subject to the notice
33 requirements in subsection (c) of this section.

SENATE BILL 943 5
1 (v) After revised bids have been submitted, negotiations with
2 bidders may not be conducted unless the procurement officer determines that there is a
3 compelling reason to negotiate.
4 (vi) After revised bids have been opened and any approval required
5 by law has been obtained, the procurement officer shall award the procurement contract to
6 the responsible bidder who submits a responsive bid [that:
7 1. is the lowest bid price;
8 2. if the invitation for revised bids so provides, is the lowest
9 evaluated bid price; or
10 3. for procurement subject to § 11–202(3) of this article,]
11 THAT is the bid most favorable to the State UNDER THE STANDARDIZED EVALUATION
12 CRITERIA UNDER SUBSECTION (G) OF THIS SECTION.
13 (4) A responsive bid or proposal shall include:
14 (I) the criteria specified in subsection (a) of this section; AND
15 (II) A STATEMENT OF THE STATE AND LOCAL ECONOMIC
16 IMPACT OF THE BID, INCLUDING:
17 1. THE PERCENTAGE OF STATE–BASED EMPLOYEES
18 WHO WILL PERFORM THE CONTRACT;
19 2. THE ANTICIPATED STATE–BASED SUBCONTRACTORS
20 THAT WILL BE UTILIZED IN THE PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT;
21 3. THE ESTIMATED STATE AND LOCAL TAXES THAT WILL
22 BE GENERATED FROM THE PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT;
23 4. THE NUMBER OF JOBS THAT WILL BE CREATED OR
24 RETAINED IN THE STATE FROM THE PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT; AND
25 5. ANY LOCATION WHERE THE CONTRACT WILL BE
26 PERFORMED.
27 (f) Not more than 30 days after the execution and approval of a procurement
28 contract in excess of the small procurement amount specified in § 13–109 of this subtitle
29 awarded under this section, or a lower amount set by the Board by regulation in accordance
30 with Title 10, Subtitle 1 of the State Government Article, a unit shall publish notice of the
31 award in eMaryland Marketplace.

6 SENATE BILL 943
1 (G) (1) FOR ANY PROCUREMENT CONTRACT AWARDED IN ACCORDANCE
2 WITH THIS SECTION, A UNIT SHALL EVALUATE PROPOSALS USING THE
3 STANDARDIZED CRITERIA UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
4 (2) (I) UNLESS OTHERWISE REQUIRED BY FEDERAL LAW, A BID
5 SHALL BE EVALUATED ON A SCALE OF 100 POINTS.
6 (II) A MAXIMUM OF 40 POINTS MAY BE AWARDED FOR THE
7 TECHNICAL MERIT OF THE BID, INCLUDING:
8 1. THE QUALITY OF THE PROPOSED METHODS OF
9 PERFORMING THE CONTRACT;
10 2. THE TECHNICAL CAPABILITY OF THE BIDDER;
11 3. THE STAFFING AND QUALIFICATIONS OF THE BIDDER;
12 AND
13 4. THE BIDDER’S COMPLIANCE WITH THE SCOPE AND
14 SPECIFICATIONS INCLUDED IN THE INVITATION FOR BIDS.
15 (III) A MAXIMUM OF 30 POINTS MAY BE AWARDED FOR THE
16 STATE AND LOCAL ECONOMIC IMPACT OF THE BID, INCLUDING:
17 1. THE BIDDER HAVING ITS PRINCIPAL PLACE OF
18 BUSINESS IN THE STATE;
19 2. THE PERCENTAGE OF THE BIDDER’S WORKFORCE
20 EMPLOYED IN THE STATE;
21 3. THE USE OF STATE–BASED SUBCONTRACTORS;
22 4. THE EXPECTED STATE AND LOCAL TAXES THAT WILL
23 BE GENERATED FROM PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT; AND
24 5. THE AMOUNT OF THE BIDDER’S CAPITAL INVESTMENT
25 AND REINVESTMENT IN THE STATE.
26 (IV) A MAXIMUM OF 20 POINTS MAY BE AWARDED FOR THE
27 TOTAL COST TO THE UNIT UNDER THE BID.
28 (V) A MAXIMUM OF 10 POINTS MAY BE AWARDED FOR:

SENATE BILL 943 7
1 1. PRIOR PERFORMANCE OF CONTRACTS WITH THE
2 STATE OR LOCAL GOVERNMENTS BY THE BIDDER; AND
3 2. THE TIMELINESS, QUALITY OF WORK PERFORMED,
4 AND COMPLIANCE HISTORY OF THE BIDDER ON ANY PRIOR CONTRACTS WITH THE
5 STATE OR LOCAL GOVERNMENTS.
6 13–104.
7 (a) Competitive sealed proposals is the preferred method for:
8 (1) human, social, cultural, or educational services; and
9 (2) security services with an expected value that is greater than
10 $1,000,000.
11 (b) (1) Whenever procurement is based on competitive sealed proposals, a
12 procurement officer shall seek proposals by issuing a request for proposals.
13 (2) A request for proposals shall include a statement of:
14 (i) the scope of the procurement contract, including the expected
15 degree of minority business enterprise participation, as provided in § 14–303(b) of this
16 article;
17 (ii) a summary of the factors used to determine the expected degree
18 of minority business enterprise participation for the procurement contract, including
19 subcontracting opportunities identified for the project, any applicable North American
20 Industry Classification System codes linked to the subcontracting opportunities, and the
21 number of certified minority business enterprises in those industries; AND
22 (iii) the factors[, including price,] UNDER SUBSECTION (H) OF THIS
23 SECTION that will be used in evaluating proposals[; and
24 (iv) the relative importance of each factor].
25 (c) A unit shall publish a request for proposals in the same manner as required
26 for an invitation for bids.
27 (d) (1) After receipt of proposals but before the procurement officer awards the
28 procurement contract, a unit may conduct discussions with an offeror to:
29 (i) obtain the best price for the State; and
30 (ii) ensure full understanding of:

8 SENATE BILL 943
1 1. the requirements of the State, as set forth in the request
2 for proposals; and
3 2. the proposal submitted by the offeror.
4 (2) If discussions are conducted, the unit:
5 (i) shall conduct the discussions in accordance with regulations
6 adopted under this Division II;
7 (ii) shall provide an opportunity to participate to each responsible
8 offeror who submits a proposal that, in the judgment of the procurement officer, is
9 reasonably susceptible of being selected for award;
10 (iii) shall treat all of those responsible offerors fairly and equally;
11 (iv) may allow all of those responsible offerors to revise their initial
12 proposals by submitting best and final offers, if discussions indicate that it would be in the
13 best interests of the State to do so;
14 (v) may conduct more than 1 series of discussions and requests for
15 best and final offers; and
16 (vi) may not disclose to an offeror any information derived from a
17 proposal of or discussions with a competing offeror.
18 (3) (i) Except as provided in subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, an
19 oral presentation is required when:
20 1. the total value of the contract is expected to exceed
21 $2,000,000 for architectural and engineering services;
22 2. the total value of the contract is expected to exceed
23 $10,000,000 for construction and construction related services; or
24 3. for any other procurement, including information
25 technology and professional services, the total value of the contract is expected to exceed
26 $5,000,000.
27 (ii) If the procurement officer makes a written determination that
28 oral presentations are unlikely to aid in the evaluation process, oral presentations are not
29 required.
30 (e) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection:
31 (i) a proposal is irrevocable for the period specified in the request
32 for proposals; and

SENATE BILL 943 9
1 (ii) a best and final offer is irrevocable for the period specified in the
2 request for best and final offers.
3 (2) A procurement officer may allow an offeror to correct or withdraw a
4 proposal or best and final offer if correction or withdrawal is:
5 (i) allowed under regulations adopted under this Division II; and
6 (ii) approved in writing by the Office of the Attorney General.
7 (f) (1) After obtaining any approval required by law, the procurement officer
8 shall award the procurement contract to the responsible offeror who submits the proposal
9 or best and final offer determined to be the most advantageous to the State considering the
10 evaluation factors [set forth in the request for proposals] UNDER SUBSECTION (H) OF
11 THIS SECTION.
12 (2) A PROPOSAL SHALL INCLUDE A STATEMENT OF THE STATE AND
13 LOCAL ECONOMIC IMPACT OF THE BID, INCLUDING:
14 (I) THE PERCENTAGE OF STATE–BASED EMPLOYEES WHO WILL
15 PERFORM THE CONTRACT;
16 (II) THE ANTICIPATED STATE–BASED SUBCONTRACTORS THAT
17 WILL BE UTILIZED IN THE PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT;
18 (III) THE ESTIMATED STATE AND LOCAL TAXES THAT WILL BE
19 GENERATED FROM THE PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT;
20 (IV) THE NUMBER OF JOBS THAT WILL BE CREATED OR
21 RETAINED IN THE STATE FROM THE PERFORMANCE OF THE CONTRACT; AND
22 (V) ANY LOCATION WHERE THE CONTRACT WILL BE
23 PERFORMED.
24 (g) A unit shall publish notice of a contract in excess of the small procurement
25 amount specified in § 13–109 of this subtitle awarded under this section, or a lower amount
26 set by the Board by regulation in accordance with Title 10, Subtitle 1 of the State
27 Government Article in eMaryland Marketplace.
28 (H) (1) FOR ANY PROCUREMENT CONTRACT AWARDED IN ACCORDANCE
29 WITH THIS SECTION, A UNIT SHALL EVALUATE PROPOSALS USING THE
30 STANDARDIZED CRITERIA UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.

